<paragraph id="8B92369E467566344BEC9F29FCE4D3D7" blockId="8.[140,1108,800,1671]" pageId="8" pageNumber="123">
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D1D467566344BEC9F29FEDBD5C7" box="[185,334,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Acrotona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avia">
<emphasis id="B959EA8C467566344BEC9F29FEDBD5C7" box="[185,334,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="123">Acrotona avia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="13162A1B467566344A089F28FE09D5C6" box="[349,412,870,897]" captionStart="Figs 1-4" captionStartId="7.[140,180,1622,1644]" captionTargetBox="[185,1061,1111,1596]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[180,1067,1105,1603]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 1-4. Dorsal habitus: Fig. 1, Acrotona avia; Fig. 2, Oligota parva; Fig. 3, Strigota ambigua; Fig. 4, Myrmecopora vaga." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3770912" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3770912/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="123">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) is newly recorded in 
<collectingCountry id="F33A760E4675663449CD9F28FD78D5C7" box="[664,749,870,896]" name="Canada" pageId="8" pageNumber="123">Canada</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="13162A1B4675663449A99F28FCDAD5C6" box="[764,847,870,897]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="10.[140,173,1622,1644]" captionTargetBox="[140,1108,873,1602]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[140,1107,873,1602]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Fig. 12. The distribution of Micralymma marinum, Aleochara litoralis, Oligota parva, Acrotona avia, and Strigota ambigua in Atlantic Canada." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3767189" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3767189/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="123">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D1D4675663448319F29FC6DD5C7" box="[868,1016,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Acrotona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avia">
<emphasis id="B959EA8C4675663448319F29FC6DD5C7" box="[868,1016,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="123">Acrotona avia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBC4B6F467566344BAB9FC4FE1AD5E3" author="Casey" box="[254,399,906,932]" firstAuthor="Casey" pageId="8" pageNumber="123" refId="ref16013" refString="Casey TL (1910) New species of the Staphylinid tribe Myrmedoniini: Memoirs on the Coleoptera 1. New Era Printing, Lancaster, 183 pp." type="book" year="1910">Casey (1910)</bibRefCitation>
on the basis of specimens collected in Rhode Island. The bionomics of the species are unknown, however, it appears that 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D1D4675663449A69FE3FCD4D580" box="[755,833,941,967]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Acrotona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avia">
<emphasis id="B959EA8C4675663449A69FE3FCD4D580" box="[755,833,941,967]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="123">A. avia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
could be associated with sandy, seacoast environments. Pomquet Beach (
<geoCoordinate id="EE1950594675663449F69F9EFCB8D5AC" box="[675,813,976,1003]" degrees="45" direction="north" minutes="39" orientation="latitude" pageId="8" pageNumber="123" precision="15" seconds="27" value="45.6575">45°39’27”N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="EE19505946756634486E9F9EFC5FD5AC" box="[827,970,976,1003]" degrees="61" direction="west" minutes="49" orientation="longitude" pageId="8" pageNumber="123" precision="15" seconds="18" value="-61.821667">61°49’18”W</geoCoordinate>
) is a coastal barrier beach that lies between Pomquet Harbour and St. Georges Bay on the Gulf of St. Lawrence in 
<collectingRegion id="49E9F87C467566344A6A9859FE5CD277" box="[319,457,1046,1073]" country="Canada" name="Nova Scotia" pageId="8" pageNumber="123">Nova Scotia</collectingRegion>
. The specimens from that locale were collected in a coastal sand dune environment adjacent to a “slack” (a temporary water body lying between two dune crests). Saunderstown (Rhode Island) is located near the mouth of Narragansett Bay where it opens up onto Long Island Sound. The Casey family farm (
<geoCoordinate id="EE19505946756634489198CEFBDAD2DD" box="[964,1103,1152,1178]" degrees="41" direction="north" minutes="30" orientation="latitude" pageId="8" pageNumber="123" precision="15" seconds="44" value="41.512222">41°30’44”N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="EE195059467566344BD998EDFE89D2F9" box="[140,284,1187,1214]" degrees="71" direction="west" minutes="25" orientation="longitude" pageId="8" pageNumber="123" precision="15" seconds="23" value="-71.42305">71°25’23”W</geoCoordinate>
), where T.L. Casey lived and carried out collecting (
<bibRefCitation id="EFBC4B6F46756634480E98EDFC4DD2FA" author="Sikes" box="[859,984,1187,1213]" firstAuthor="Sikes" pageId="8" pageNumber="123" refId="ref17974" refString="Sikes DS (2004) The beetle fauna of Rhode Island: an annotated checklist. Kingston, Rhode Island: Rhode Island Natural History Survey, volume 3, 296 pp. http: // collections 2. eeb. uconn. edu / collections / insects / ribf / ribfcontents. html [accessed 30 July 2008]" type="book" year="2004">Sikes 2004</bibRefCitation>
), is located 0.35 km from the seacoast, immediately adjacent to a barrier beach and coastal lagoon environment very similar to the Pomquet Beach site in 
<collectingRegion id="49E9F87C4675663449AE98A4FC13D343" box="[763,902,1258,1284]" country="Canada" name="Nova Scotia" pageId="8" pageNumber="123">Nova Scotia</collectingRegion>
. Although there is no specific information that Casey collected the 
<typeStatus id="5496883C4675663449F09943FD41D360" box="[677,724,1293,1319]" pageId="8" pageNumber="123">type</typeStatus>
specimens from precisely this site, it appears probable that 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D1D467566344AF7997EFE67D30D" box="[418,498,1328,1354]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Acrotona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avia">
<emphasis id="B959EA8C467566344AF7997EFE67D30D" box="[418,498,1328,1354]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="123">A. avia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is associated with such coastal environments. 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D1D467566344F55997EFE30D32A" authority="(Gyllenhal, 1808)" baseAuthorityName="Gyllenhal" baseAuthorityYear="1808" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" genus="Cercyon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="litoralis">
<emphasis id="B959EA8C467566344F55997EFF4FD32A" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="123">Cercyon litoralis</emphasis>
(Gyllenhal, 1808)
</taxonomicName>
[
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D1D467566344AE7991DFDCCD329" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[434,601,1363,1390]" class="Insecta" family="Hydrophilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Hydrophilidae</taxonomicName>
] and 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D1D4675663449C3991AFB8DD32A" authority="Melsheimer, 1844" authorityName="Melsheimer" authorityYear="1844" box="[662,1048,1363,1390]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Stenus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erythropus">
<emphasis id="B959EA8C4675663449C3991AFCDED32A" box="[662,843,1363,1390]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="123">Stenus erythropus</emphasis>
Melsheimer, 1844
</taxonomicName>
[
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D1D467566344F73991DFE96D3D6" baseAuthorityName="Herman" baseAuthorityYear="2001" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Staphylinidae</taxonomicName>
] were collected together with 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D1D4675663449199939FD0FD3D7" box="[588,666,1399,1425]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Acrotona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avia">
<emphasis id="B959EA8C4675663449199939FD0FD3D7" box="[588,666,1399,1425]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="123">A. avia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
at Pomquet Beach.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B92369E467566344BEC99D4FD92D007" blockId="8.[140,1108,800,1671]" pageId="8" pageNumber="123">
Until this present report from 
<collectingRegion id="49E9F87C46756634497399D4FD27D3F3" box="[550,690,1434,1460]" country="Canada" name="Nova Scotia" pageId="8" pageNumber="123">Nova Scotia</collectingRegion>
the species has not otherwise been reported from outside 
<collectingRegion id="49E9F87C467566344ADB99F3FDBCD390" box="[398,553,1469,1495]" country="United States of America" name="Rhode Island" pageId="8" pageNumber="123">Rhode Island</collectingRegion>
. It is likely that it is not as restricted in distribution as these limited records would appear to indicate, but rather 
<bibRefCitation id="EFBC4B6F46756634482F99AFFBC1D3BD" author="Sikes DS" box="[890,1108,1504,1531]" firstAuthor="as Sikes" pageId="8" pageNumber="123" refId="ref17974" refString="Sikes DS (2004) The beetle fauna of Rhode Island: an annotated checklist. Kingston, Rhode Island: Rhode Island Natural History Survey, volume 3, 296 pp. http: // collections 2. eeb. uconn. edu / collections / insects / ribf / ribfcontents. html [accessed 30 July 2008]" type="book" year="2004">as Sikes (2004: 10)</bibRefCitation>
pointed out, “…even in well-studied, temperate regions, a great deal of basic taxonomic work remains to be done”.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B92369E467566374BEC9A04FB8CD740" blockId="8.[140,1108,800,1671]" lastBlockId="11.[140,1108,166,264]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="126" pageId="8" pageNumber="123">
<bibRefCitation id="EFBC4B6F467566344BEC9A04FEF5D023" author="Gusarov" box="[185,352,1610,1636]" firstAuthor="Gusarov" pageId="8" pageNumber="123" refId="ref16399" refString="Gusarov VI (2001 - 2003) A catalogue of the athetine species of America north of Mexico (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Aleocharinae: Athetini). http: // nhm. ku. edu / ksem / peet / catalogs / cataweb. htm [accessed 30 July 2008]" type="url" year="2001">
Gusarov (
<date id="FF93105E467566344A709A04FEF5D023" box="[293,352,1610,1636]" pageId="8" pageNumber="123" value="2001" valueMax="2003">2001</date>
</bibRefCitation>
-2003) listed this name as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D1D46756634483B9A04FEDED0C0" authority="Bernhauer, 1909" authorityName="Bernhauer" authorityYear="1909" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Acrotona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subpygmaea">
<emphasis id="B959EA8C46756634483B9A04FBC1D023" box="[878,1108,1610,1636]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="123">Acrotona subpygmaea</emphasis>
Bernhauer, 1909
</taxonomicName>
. However, we have specimens at hand from 
<collectingRegion id="49E9F87C4675663448699A23FC7AD0C0" box="[828,1007,1645,1671]" country="Canada" name="New Brunswick" pageId="8" pageNumber="123">New Brunswick</collectingRegion>
(see Klimaszewski et al. 2005: 14, 15, 34) examined by him and identified as 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D1D4677663648E69CE9FE97D6A3" authority="Bernhauer" authorityName="Bernhauer" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Acrotona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subpygmaea">
<emphasis id="B959EA8C4677663648E69CE9FBC1D687" box="[947,1108,166,193]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">A. subpygmaea</emphasis>
Bernhauer
</taxonomicName>
, which clearly belong to a different species. For this reason we provisionally retain 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D1D467766364B869CA3FEB5D740" box="[211,288,237,263]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Acrotona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avia">
<emphasis id="B959EA8C467766364B869CA3FEB5D740" box="[211,288,237,263]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">A. avia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a distinct species until proper revisionary studies are finalized. We confirm however, that 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D1D467766364A0B9D5EFDEED76D" authority="(Casey, 1910)" baseAuthorityName="Casey" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[350,635,272,298]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Acrotona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="puritana">
<emphasis id="B959EA8C467766364A0B9D5EFE4ED76D" box="[350,475,272,298]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">A. puritana</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFBC4B6F467766364ABC9D5EFDE6D76D" author="Casey" box="[489,627,272,298]" firstAuthor="Casey" pageId="10" pageNumber="125" refId="ref16013" refString="Casey TL (1910) New species of the Staphylinid tribe Myrmedoniini: Memoirs on the Coleoptera 1. New Era Printing, Lancaster, 183 pp." type="book" year="1910">Casey, 1910</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
[originally 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D1D4677663649AE9D5EFCFDD76D" authorityName="Mulsant &amp; Rey" authorityYear="1873" box="[763,872,272,298]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Colpodota" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B959EA8C4677663649AE9D5EFCFDD76D" box="[763,872,272,298]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">Colpodota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
] is a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D1D467766364BFD9D7AFEC6D70A" authority="(Casey)" baseAuthorityName="Casey" box="[168,339,307,334]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Acrotona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avia">
<emphasis id="B959EA8C467766364BFD9D7AFF60D70A" box="[168,245,308,334]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">A. avia</emphasis>
(Casey)
</taxonomicName>
. We were able to examine four 
<typeStatus id="5496883C4677663649FD9D7AFC93D709" box="[680,774,308,334]" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">syntypes</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D1D46776636487C9D7AFCE0D70A" box="[809,885,308,334]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Acrotona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avia">
<emphasis id="B959EA8C46776636487C9D7AFCE0D70A" box="[809,885,308,334]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">A. avia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingRegion id="49E9F87C4677663648EC9D7DFBDAD70A" box="[953,1103,307,333]" country="United States of America" name="Rhode Island" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">Rhode Island</collectingRegion>
, Boston Neck, housed in the Casey collection in 
<collectingRegion id="49E9F87C4677663649E09D18FCA9D737" box="[693,828,342,368]" country="United States of America" name="Washington" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">Washington</collectingRegion>
(USNM). We designate here the female bearing the following labels as the 
<typeStatus id="5496883C4677663649939D34FCBAD7D3" box="[710,815,378,404]" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">lectotype</typeStatus>
: “R.I., a 
<emphasis id="B959EA8C4677663648D99D34FC38D7D4" box="[908,941,378,403]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">via</emphasis>
-3, 
<typeStatus id="5496883C4677663648B09D34FF29D7F0" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">paralectotype</typeStatus>
USNM, 38993, Casey bequest 1925”, and Gusarov’s unpublished 
<typeStatus id="5496883C4677663648EA9DD3FBC1D7F0" box="[959,1108,413,439]" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">paralectotype</typeStatus>
label: “ 
<typeStatus id="5496883C467766364B8D9D8EFEE8D79D" box="[216,381,448,474]" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">paralectotypus</typeStatus>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D1D467766364ADD9D8EFDE0D79D" authority="Casey" authorityName="Casey" authorityYear="1910" box="[392,629,448,474]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Colpodota" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avia">
<emphasis id="B959EA8C467766364ADD9D8EFDBED79D" box="[392,555,448,474]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">Colpodota avia</emphasis>
Casey
</taxonomicName>
, female, V.I. Gusarov des. 2000” (USNM) [genital structures well preserved]. The remaining three specimens then become 
<typeStatus id="5496883C467766364F4F9DAAFF6BD467" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">paralectotypes</typeStatus>
: R.I., Casey bequest 1925, 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D1D4677663649639E49FDF1D467" authorityName="Casey" authorityYear="1910" box="[566,612,519,544]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Colpodota" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avia">
<emphasis id="B959EA8C4677663649639E49FDF1D467" box="[566,612,519,544]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">avia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-2, 
<typeStatus id="5496883C4677663649D99E49FD79D466" box="[652,748,519,545]" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">paratype</typeStatus>
USNM 38993, 
<typeStatus id="5496883C4677663648FE9E48FBC5D467" box="[939,1104,518,544]" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">paralectotypus</typeStatus>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D1D467766364BD99E64FEE3D403" authority="Casey" authorityName="Casey" authorityYear="1910" box="[140,374,554,580]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Colpodota" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avia">
<emphasis id="B959EA8C467766364BD99E64FEB8D404" box="[140,301,554,580]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">Colpodota avia</emphasis>
Casey
</taxonomicName>
, male, V.I. Gusarov des. 2000 (USNM) male [aedeagus missing in the attached vial]; R.I. same labels as the 
<typeStatus id="5496883C4677663649189E03FD27D420" box="[589,690,589,615]" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">lectotype</typeStatus>
except, 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D1D46776636485E9E00FCACD420" authorityName="Casey" authorityYear="1910" box="[779,825,590,615]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Colpodota" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avia">
<emphasis id="B959EA8C46776636485E9E00FCACD420" box="[779,825,590,615]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">avia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-1, Type USNM 387993, Gusarov’s unpublished 
<typeStatus id="5496883C467766364AC19E3EFE6CD4CD" box="[404,505,624,650]" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">lectotype</typeStatus>
designation label 2000 (USNM) 
<specimenCount id="9D2BFD174677663648289E3EFC74D4CD" box="[893,993,624,650]" pageId="10" pageNumber="125" type="female">1 female</specimenCount>
; and R.I., 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D1D467766364BD99EDAFF2FD4EA" authorityName="Casey" authorityYear="1910" box="[140,186,660,685]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Colpodota" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="avia">
<emphasis id="B959EA8C467766364BD99EDAFF2FD4EA" box="[140,186,660,685]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">avia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-4 (USNM) 
<specimenCount id="9D2BFD17467766364A129EDDFE3CD4EA" box="[327,425,659,685]" pageId="10" pageNumber="125" type="female">1 female</specimenCount>
. We have designated a female specimen as a 
<typeStatus id="5496883C4677663648C69EDDFC6DD4EA" box="[915,1016,659,685]" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">lectotype</typeStatus>
because the female of this species may be easily distinguished by having the apical margin of sternite eight deeply emarginate (
<figureCitation id="13162A1B467766364A819E94FDB6D4B3" box="[468,547,730,756]" captionStart="Figs 5-11" captionStartId="9.[140,180,1590,1612]" captionTargetBox="[154,1098,175,1539]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[140,1108,165,1542]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figs 5-11. Genital structures of Acrotona avia: 5-8 male: Fig. 5, median lobe of aedeagus in dorsal view, and Fig. 6 in lateral view; Fig. 7, tergite VIII, and Fig. 8 sternite VIII; figures 9-11 female: Fig. 9, spermatheca; Fig. 10, tergite VIII; Fig. 11, sternite VIII." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3770914" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3770914/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
) and by the shape of the spermatheca (
<figureCitation id="13162A1B4677663648879E94FB81D4B3" box="[978,1044,730,756]" captionStart="Figs 5-11" captionStartId="9.[140,180,1590,1612]" captionTargetBox="[154,1098,175,1539]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[140,1108,165,1542]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figs 5-11. Genital structures of Acrotona avia: 5-8 male: Fig. 5, median lobe of aedeagus in dorsal view, and Fig. 6 in lateral view; Fig. 7, tergite VIII, and Fig. 8 sternite VIII; figures 9-11 female: Fig. 9, spermatheca; Fig. 10, tergite VIII; Fig. 11, sternite VIII." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3770914" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3770914/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="125">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
), and because the male genital structures were missing in the only male specimen in the type series. To avoid potential confusion in identification of this species in the future we provide for the first time the images of the body and the genital structures (
<figureCitation id="13162A1B4676663748E19CE8FB95D686" box="[948,1024,166,193]" captionStart="Figs 1-4" captionStartId="7.[140,180,1622,1644]" captionTargetBox="[185,1061,1111,1596]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[180,1067,1105,1603]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 1-4. Dorsal habitus: Fig. 1, Acrotona avia; Fig. 2, Oligota parva; Fig. 3, Strigota ambigua; Fig. 4, Myrmecopora vaga." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3770912" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3770912/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="126">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13162A1B467666374F5B9CE8FBD0D686" box="[1038,1093,166,193]" captionStart="Figs 5-11" captionStartId="9.[140,180,1590,1612]" captionTargetBox="[154,1098,175,1539]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[140,1108,165,1542]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figs 5-11. Genital structures of Acrotona avia: 5-8 male: Fig. 5, median lobe of aedeagus in dorsal view, and Fig. 6 in lateral view; Fig. 7, tergite VIII, and Fig. 8 sternite VIII; figures 9-11 female: Fig. 9, spermatheca; Fig. 10, tergite VIII; Fig. 11, sternite VIII." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3770914" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3770914/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="126">5-11</figureCitation>
). The body and the genital structures of 
<taxonomicName id="4C2D4D1D4676663749639C84FCF4D6A2" authority="(Bernhauer)" baseAuthorityName="Bernhauer" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[566,865,202,229]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Acrotona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="126" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subpygmaea">
<emphasis id="B959EA8C4676663749639C84FD41D6A3" box="[566,724,202,228]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="126">A. subpygmaea</emphasis>
(Bernhauer)
</taxonomicName>
are published in Figs. 
<quantity id="4CD59B7B467666374BD99CA3FEA3D740" box="[140,310,237,264]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8302732" metricValueMax="3.0225999999999997" metricValueMin="0.6379464" pageId="11" pageNumber="126" unit="in" value="72.05799999999999" valueMax="119.0" valueMin="25.116">25, 116-119 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation id="EFBC4B6F467666374A689CA3FDF3D74F" author="Klimaszewski" box="[317,614,237,264]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Klimaszewski" pageId="11" pageNumber="126" pagination="1 - 48" refId="ref17028" refString="Klimaszewski J, Sweeney J, Price J, Pelletier G (2005) Rove beetles (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae) in red spruce stands, eastern Canada: diversity, abundance, and descriptions of new species. The Canadian Entomologist 137: 1 - 48." type="journal article" year="2005">Klimaszewski et al. (2005)</bibRefCitation>
, based on V.I. Gusarov’s identification.
</paragraph>
